ÜgÂ]<?php exit; ?>a:1:{s:7:"content";O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1266";s:4:"name";s:8:"Dyslexia";s:4:"slug";s:8:"dyslexia";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1266";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:2920:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Dyslexia is a learning disability that involves problems with reading due to difficulty with recognizing speech sounds and understanding how they connect with words and letters.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Also called reading disability, dyslexia influences parts of the brain that handles language processing.Â  70-80% of people with awful reading skills are presumably dyslexic. 15-20% of the population, is affected by a language-based learning disorder. Dyslexia is the most prevalent of language-based learning disorder.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Virtually the same percentage of males and females have this disorder.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Â </span><b>Symptoms of dyslexia</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Symptoms of dyslexia can be hard to identify before your kid enters school, however, some early signs may point towards a problem.</span>

<b>Before school</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Signs that a child may be susceptible to dyslexia include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Learning new words at a snail's pace (slowly)</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Late talking</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Difficulty forming words properly.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Problem with playing rhyming games or understanding nursery rhymes.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>School-age</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">When your child is in school, symptoms of dyslexia include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Reading below the normal level for age</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">A difficulty with understanding what he/she hears.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Inability to find the right word or answer to a question.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Spelling difficulty</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">The same symptoms still persist after school.</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Â </span><b>Causes of Dyslexia</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Dyslexia often runs in families. It is usually associated with certain genes that influence the way the brain processes language and reading.</span>

<b>Risk factors of Dyslexia</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Dyslexia risk factors include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Family history</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Early birth</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Child's exposure to drugs or infection that hinders brain development in the fetus.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Treatment of Dyslexia</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There is no sure way to correct the hidden brain disorder that causes dyslexia. However, detecting early and making arrangements for the appropriate treatment can help</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"0";}}